which Kate, Andy, and I took, and how we are using that in our work. So I'll go ahead and share the

00:13:34.239 --> 00:13:42.640
screen. So I'm going to share what we are doing right here with exponentially weighted moving

00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:50.559
average. I'll go into the details of what that is and how we are using R to do this and help

00:13:50.559 --> 00:13:55.679
keep track of our infectious disease trends and outbreaks here at the health district.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:14:03.359
And the data that I used today is the one that POSIT shared during the training.

00:14:05.359 --> 00:14:12.239
It's COVID data, which includes the number of cases, deaths over time in the United States,

00:14:12.239 --> 00:14:21.760
and we have state level data as well in that data set. So I created a core document that

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:28.880
describes the code chunks and also a little bit information on what the statistical methods that

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:36.080
we are using here. So the first code chunk here, it shows all the needed libraries that we have to do

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:47.359
load in R to perform these, which includes the DPL, YR, the QCC, which is used to calculate the

00:14:47.359 --> 00:14:53.760
control limits, which I'll go into detail later, then for plotting GG plot and for importing the

00:14:53.760 --> 00:15:00.960
data, I use the read Excel. So what is exponentially weighted moving average? It's a

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:07.200
statistical method used for analyzing time series data, which is usually the type of data that we

00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:14.000
deal with on a daily basis. It helps us to track the infectious disease trends over time. And what

00:15:14.559 --> 00:15:21.760
this method do is that it assigns different weights to different data points, and we can

00:15:21.760 --> 00:15:26.320
give more significance to the recent observations compared to the previous, which is very important

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:33.599
in our realm, since we need to be more responsive to immediate changes and more real-time changes.

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:40.960
And then here you can see the formula that calculates the exponentially weighted moving

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:45.599
average, and the alpha here, which is the multiplier, is also called a smoothing factor.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:54.799
And as we assign higher values to alpha, it gives more weightage to more recent data trends.

00:15:54.799 --> 00:16:01.679
So in R, the code chunk, first step is to import the dataset using the read.csv.

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:12.320
Then step two, this dataset contains data for all states across the country. So I just

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:18.640
wanted to focus on one state, so I used the filter function to filter the state New York's data

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:24.799
and assign the name as COVID filtered. And then the next step, the third one, is to

00:16:25.919 --> 00:16:33.119
format the date. And step four is to assign the alpha value, which we discussed earlier,

00:16:33.119 --> 00:16:39.679
which I set at 0.3, which is the usual practice. But as you assign higher values,

00:16:39.679 --> 00:16:44.320
it gives more weightage to more recent data. But 0.3 is a reasonable practice.

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:53.520
And step five is to calculate the initial value of the exponentially weighted average.

00:16:53.520 --> 00:17:00.000
We are assigning an initial value from the column cases, which tracks the number of cases in New

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:08.160
York City over time. So the first row in column one is assigned as the initial value here,

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:17.119
and we move forward to the step six, where we are actually initializing the EWMA column.

00:17:18.319 --> 00:17:28.160
So here I'm creating a column called EWMA using mutate function, and then assigning the initial

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:36.160
value to the first row of the column and assigning the rest of value as NAs for now. And on step

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:42.560
seven, we are calculating those NAs that we assigned previously, where from the second row

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:51.199
onwards, we are calculating the EWMA based on the previous case number. And the formula here

00:17:51.199 --> 00:17:59.359
that I have put in is from this one up here, where we are multiplying with the smoothing factor

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:07.599
and observation at time t, and then we add that to one minus the smoothing factor into the

00:18:07.599 --> 00:18:15.920
observation on the previous row. So that will give us the column values for the exponentially

00:18:15.920 --> 00:18:22.640
weighted moving average, and I will create a separate column in our data set. And the next

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:29.199
step is to identify our control limits, where we are tracking this exponentially weighted moving

00:18:29.199 --> 00:18:36.239
average, but we need to know the trigger points where we are crossing that limit. And that is

00:18:36.239 --> 00:18:42.239
where the control charts come into play. So what the purpose of control chart is to track the

00:18:42.239 --> 00:18:50.000
progression of a specific event over time. And here I'm applying the exponentially weighted

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:57.760
average that we calculated into the control chart. And the package that is used is the

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:07.119
QCC package that we loaded earlier at first. And here is the code chunk that calculates the

00:19:07.119 --> 00:19:15.920
control chart values. And the type of chart that I have put in here is x-bar dot one.

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:24.239
And what the x-bar chart do is that it's suitable for subgroup data. So if you have time series

00:19:24.239 --> 00:19:31.040
data like in our situation where we are tracking the number of cases over weeks or days, months,

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:37.520
then the x-bar chart is the go-to. So what it does is it monitors the average or mean of the

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:44.319
number of cases over time. And the central line of the chart will indicate the mean. And there'll

00:19:44.319 --> 00:19:49.359
be a lower confidence and an upper confidence limit that will be calculated, which is usually

00:19:49.359 --> 00:19:56.079
two to three standard deviations from the mean. And I have set and default is two standard

00:19:56.079 --> 00:20:03.040
deviations. You can change that to three standard deviation if needed in this code chunk on step eight.

00:20:04.239 --> 00:20:12.880
And step nine would be to extract these means and the upper and lower confidence limits that

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:22.640
we calculated. So here the mean can be extracted using this first code where from the control

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:29.680
chart we are extracting the center. Then for lower confidence limit, similarly you can use these code

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:37.599
chunks to extract those. And step 10 would be to apply these limits into our moving average that

00:20:37.599 --> 00:20:46.239
we calculated earlier. So step 10, identify points where the EWMA exceeds the upper confidence limit.

00:20:47.199 --> 00:20:53.520
So here in the data sets COVID filtered, I'm creating a new column called out of control

00:20:55.839 --> 00:21:02.719
where when the EWMA values are more than the upper confidence limit, it will be assigned as true.

00:21:02.719 --> 00:21:07.280
And when it's less than the upper confidence limit, it will be assigned as a false.

00:21:08.079 --> 00:21:16.560
In the new column and step 11, once we have this data finalized, then we just have to plot it

00:21:16.560 --> 00:21:24.479
using the ggplot function. So on the x-axis we are doing the date and the y-axis we are doing

00:21:24.479 --> 00:21:30.800
the exponentially weighted moving average that we calculated. And I'm doing a line plot. So I have

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:42.959
the geom line here. Then the geom ribbon function here is to plot the upper and the lower confidence

00:21:42.959 --> 00:21:50.880
limit that we calculated from the control chart. And the geom point marks the actual data points

00:21:51.599 --> 00:22:02.000
in the data set. And again, the geom hedge lines are to plot the upper and lower confidence limit.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:07.119
So in this graph, you can see the geom ribbon creates this gray shaded ribbon area and the

00:22:07.119 --> 00:22:13.599
geom hedge lines creates those upper median and the lower confidence limits from the control chart.

00:22:14.160 --> 00:22:23.280
Then I am assigning the color manuals to black and red where if the column out of control is true,

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:27.920
then it will be marked as red, which means that the exponential weighted average for that

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:35.760
particular time point exceeds the upper confidence limit. And if it is a no, then it will be assigned

00:22:35.760 --> 00:22:43.439
a black color. So that's how this plot is created. So here you can see over time we are tracking

00:22:43.439 --> 00:22:49.439
the exponentially weighted average of the number of cases in New York. And the upper confidence

00:22:49.439 --> 00:22:58.400
limit is this upper dashed black line. And whenever we see the number of cases going above that limit,

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:03.359
it is indicating that it is more than usual, more than expected number of cases for that

00:23:03.359 --> 00:23:12.079
particular time point. And it triggers us to see what's going on, to look further into what's going

00:23:12.079 --> 00:23:16.319
on, whether it's an outbreak, what else is happening, what needs to be done at this point

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:23.520
to kind of control the spread of the disease. And the purpose of doing this exponentially

00:23:23.520 --> 00:23:29.040
weighted average is that it has several advantages. First is the sensitivity to

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:35.359
recent data that I described earlier. We can assign that smoothing factor for the

00:23:35.599 --> 00:23:43.839
plot to be more responsive to more recent data, which is very important in our work.

00:23:43.839 --> 00:23:50.479
And then it's flexible. So we can adjust the weight parameter and the calibration parameters

00:23:50.479 --> 00:23:55.680
to allow customization. For example, when we are looking into the data trends, if we know

00:23:57.599 --> 00:24:03.439
instead of looking across the data to calculate the upper limit, we can just pick and choose those

00:24:03.439 --> 00:24:08.719
time points where we know that the data has been stable to calculate our baseline and upper limits.

00:24:10.079 --> 00:24:16.160
So there is that flexibility there. And how we use this in our work is to,

00:24:17.199 --> 00:24:24.479
most recently, is to identify and track a pertussis outbreak that's ongoing in southwest Idaho.

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:31.359
I have not shared our data and also the code chunks that I used to calculate this particular

00:24:31.359 --> 00:24:35.599
